<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<worksheet>
  <title>Section 2.4 - Linear independence Part 2</title>
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li><p>What does it mean for a set of vectors to be linearly dependent? Linearly independent?</p></li>
      <li><p>What can you say about the pivots of a matrix if the columns of that matrix are a linearly dependent set of vectors?</p></li>
      <li><p>What is the maximum number of vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^m</m> that can be linearly dependent?</p></li>
      <li><p>When there is a non-trivial solution to the homogeneous equation <m>A\xvec=\zerovec</m>, what can you say about the columns of the matrix <m>A</m> (in terms of linear dependence/independence)?</p></li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>Consider the matrices 
  <md>
  A = 
  \left[
    \begin{array}{cccc}
      3 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 1 \\
      1 \amp -1 \amp 3 \amp 7 \\
      3 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 5 \\
      -1 \amp 2 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\
    \end{array}
  \right],\hspace*{24pt}
  B = 
  \left[
    \begin{array}{cccc}
      3 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 4 \\
      1 \amp -1 \amp 3 \amp -1 \\
      3 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 3 \\
      -1 \amp 2 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\
    \end{array}
  \right].
  </md></p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1.5in">
      <statement>
        <p>Are the columns of <m>A</m> linearly independent?  Are the columns
  of <m>B</m> linearly independent?   Explain your thinking.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1.25in">
      <statement>
        <p>For the matrix above whose columns are linearly dependent,
  express one of the vectors as a linear combination of the others.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <task workspace="0.9in">
      <statement>
        <p>Explain why seven vectors in <m>\real^5</m> cannot be linearly
  independent.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="0.9in">
      <statement>
        <p>What is the largest number of vectors in <m>\real^5</m> that can be
  linearly independent?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="0.9in">
      <statement>
        <p>If you have three vectors in <m>\real^5</m>, can you guarantee that they
  are linearly independent?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>Suppose that <m>\vvec_1, \vvec_2, \ldots, \vvec_n</m> are vectors in
  <m>\real^{24}</m> that are linearly independent and that span <m>\real^{24}</m>.</p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>What can you say about the pivot positions of the matrix <m>A</m> whose
  columns are <m>\vvec_1, \vvec_2, \ldots, \vvec_n</m>?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>How many vectors are there in this set?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Suppose that <m>\bvec</m> is a vector in <m>\real^{24}</m>.  Explain how you
  know that <m>\bvec</m> can be written as a linear combination of
  <m>\vvec_1,\vvec_2, \ldots,\vvec_n</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Suppose that <m>\bvec</m> is a vector in <m>\real^{24}</m>.  Explain how you
  know that <m>\bvec</m> can be written as a linear combination of
  <m>\vvec_1,\vvec_2, \ldots,\vvec_n</m> in exactly one way.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>What can you say about the solution to the homogeneous equation
  <m>A\xvec = \zerovec</m>?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="1in">
    <introduction>
      <p>Suppose that <m>\vvec_1,\vvec_2,\ldots,\vvec_n</m> are a set of
  vectors and that <m>\vvec_3</m> is a scalar multiple of <m>\vvec_7</m>.</p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>What
  can you say about the linear independence/dependence of this set of
  vectors?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>If <m>\vvec_1,\vvec_2,\ldots,\vvec_n</m> is a linearly independent set of
  vectors, is it necessarily true that one vector is a scalar multiple
  of another one?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>Suppose that <m>A</m> is a matrix such that the equation
  <m>A\xvec=\bvec</m> has exactly one solution for every vector <m>\bvec</m>.</p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>What can you say about the linear dependence/independence of the
  columns of <m>A</m>?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>What can you say about the span of the columns of <m>A</m>?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

</worksheet>
